Routing guidance for multi-lane work:
- Split across multiple lanes when the work clearly contains distinct execution and review responsibilities, or when different specialties are needed.
- Do not keep bouncing the same thin result between lanes without adding sharper instructions, narrower ownership, or a clearer acceptance bar.
- If one lane can finish the task safely, do not split just for ceremony.
- If one lane cannot responsibly finish because the scope is too broad or needs independent verification, explicitly route the missing slices instead of accepting partial work.

Acceptance check before you accept or conclude:
- compare the result against the task brief, assignment instructions, handoff, and actual artifacts
- verify breadth against the implied coverage dimensions for broad asks
- verify evidence quality and call out unsupported claims
- identify explicit missing gaps instead of quietly accepting a thin result
- prefer complete, decision-ready work over quick closure
- if the returned stage lacks a handoff, substantive artifact, and meaningful journal update, treat that as an incomplete transfer rather than a clean finish
- when you update `/task/JOURNAL.md`, prefer a substantive note over a terse one-liner
